WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:02.790
Time for a big one:

00:00:02.790 --> 00:00:05.297
moving a RUNNING app to another machine,

00:00:05.297 --> 00:00:06.371
while it runs.

00:00:06.371 --> 00:00:08.878
We'll watch a live counter beating in

00:00:08.878 --> 00:00:09.952
the app's memory,

00:00:09.952 --> 00:00:11.742
move everything with one command,

00:00:11.742 --> 00:00:14.249
and see the counter just keep counting

00:00:14.249 --> 00:00:15.681
on the new machine.

00:00:16.452 --> 00:00:18.562
It works in two phases.

00:00:18.562 --> 00:00:21.093
Phase one copies the bulk while

00:00:21.093 --> 00:00:22.781
the app keeps running.

00:00:22.781 --> 00:00:25.312
Phase two checkpoints the live processes,

00:00:25.312 --> 00:00:27.843
carries over the final delta plus

00:00:27.843 --> 00:00:29.109
the process state,

00:00:29.109 --> 00:00:31.640
and resumes everything on the new

00:00:31.640 --> 00:00:32.062
machine.

00:00:32.062 --> 00:00:34.594
So the downtime is the delta,

00:00:34.594 --> 00:00:35.859
not the data.

00:00:35.859 --> 00:00:38.391
And the app never knows it

00:00:38.391 --> 00:00:38.813
moved.

00:00:42.089 --> 00:00:42.841
Meet pulse.

00:00:42.841 --> 00:00:45.473
It keeps a counter in process memory

00:00:45.473 --> 00:00:48.105
and prints a beat every five seconds.

00:00:48.105 --> 00:00:50.738
The counter is at six and climbing,

00:00:50.738 --> 00:00:52.994
and it lives in RAM only.

00:00:52.994 --> 00:00:55.626
Restart the process and it starts over

00:00:55.626 --> 00:00:56.378
at one.

00:00:58.878 --> 00:01:00.088
A live counter,

00:01:00.088 --> 00:01:01.299
beating in memory.

00:01:01.299 --> 00:01:02.509
That's our evidence.

00:01:05.834 --> 00:01:07.456
One command moves it,

00:01:07.456 --> 00:01:07.861
live.

00:01:07.861 --> 00:01:09.888
Phase one transfers the bulk,

00:01:09.888 --> 00:01:12.726
two gigabytes in about half a minute,

00:01:12.726 --> 00:01:14.753
while the source keeps running.

00:01:14.753 --> 00:01:15.970
Then the cutover:

00:01:15.970 --> 00:01:17.997
it checkpoints the running processes,

00:01:17.997 --> 00:01:20.429
carries the last few megabytes across,

00:01:20.429 --> 00:01:22.862
and prints the downtime right there.

00:01:22.862 --> 00:01:24.078
About twenty seconds,

00:01:24.078 --> 00:01:26.105
for a two gigabyte move.

00:02:35.878 --> 00:02:38.571
Two gigabytes moved while the app kept running.

00:02:38.571 --> 00:02:41.263
The downtime line shows what the move actually

00:02:41.263 --> 00:02:41.599
cost.

00:02:45.846 --> 00:02:47.309
Check the new machine:

00:02:47.309 --> 00:02:48.406
there it is.

00:02:48.406 --> 00:02:48.772
Mounted,

00:02:48.772 --> 00:02:49.503
Docker running,

00:02:49.503 --> 00:02:50.600
two containers up.

00:02:53.835 --> 00:02:54.784
Same repo,

00:02:54.784 --> 00:02:55.733
new home,

00:02:55.733 --> 00:02:56.682
already running.

00:02:59.946 --> 00:03:01.117
And the source?

00:03:01.117 --> 00:03:03.069
The repository is still listed,

00:03:03.069 --> 00:03:05.022
but look at the row:

00:03:05.022 --> 00:03:05.802
not mounted,

00:03:05.802 --> 00:03:06.583
no Docker,

00:03:06.583 --> 00:03:07.364
zero containers.

00:03:07.364 --> 00:03:08.926
Nothing runs here anymore.

00:03:08.926 --> 00:03:11.268
The image stays behind on purpose,

00:03:11.268 --> 00:03:14.001
as the base for the next delta

00:03:14.001 --> 00:03:14.392
transfer.

00:03:17.392 --> 00:03:18.478
Stopped and unmounted.

00:03:18.478 --> 00:03:21.012
The leftover image is a delta base,

00:03:21.012 --> 00:03:22.459
not a running app.

00:03:25.797 --> 00:03:27.284
Now the punchline.

00:03:27.284 --> 00:03:29.266
The counter reads seventeen,

00:03:29.266 --> 00:03:29.761
eighteen,

00:03:29.761 --> 00:03:30.257
nineteen,

00:03:30.257 --> 00:03:31.248
still climbing.

00:03:31.248 --> 00:03:34.221
It picked up exactly where the

00:03:34.221 --> 00:03:37.194
checkpoint froze it instead of starting

00:03:37.194 --> 00:03:38.681
over at one.

00:03:38.681 --> 00:03:41.654
The process never noticed it changed

00:03:41.654 --> 00:03:42.150
machines.

00:03:44.650 --> 00:03:46.054
The counter kept counting.

00:03:46.054 --> 00:03:47.810
Process memory made the trip.

00:03:48.621 --> 00:03:50.671
The counter never reset.

00:03:50.671 --> 00:03:51.183
Memory,

00:03:51.183 --> 00:03:51.695
database,

00:03:51.695 --> 00:03:52.208
files,

00:03:52.208 --> 00:03:54.770
all of it just changed

00:03:54.770 --> 00:03:55.282
machines.

00:03:55.282 --> 00:03:56.307
Next up,

00:03:56.307 --> 00:03:58.869
we'll see why the second

00:03:58.869 --> 00:04:01.431
transfer is always the fast

00:04:01.431 --> 00:04:01.943
one.
